Go is not especially object-oriented and doesn't have inheritance. Simple cases of inheritance can be ported with embedding. class B : A { } Can sometimes be ported as: type A struct { }
type B struct { A
} We've embedded A inside B, so B inherit all the methods and fields of A. It doesn't work for virtual functions. There is no good way to directly port code that uses virtual functions. One option to emulate virtual function is to use embedding of structs and function pointers. This essentially re-implements virtual table that Java gives you for free as part of object implementation. Another option is to write a stand-alone function that dispatches the right function for a given type by using type switch.

